data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work without needing an `unsafe` context — you can write:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[5];
```

On this 64-bit system, each element is 8 bytes. The values are read/written just like any other `Span<T>`. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint`/`nuint` became first-class types backed by `IntPtr`/`UIntPtr`.
